# Review — Podcast Dashboard & Episode Pages

**Platform:** Bitcoin Treasury Solutions Internal Platform
**Surfaces reviewed:** `/news/podcasts` (dashboard), `/news/podcasts/[id]` (episode)
**Reviewer brief:** State-of-play + prioritised improvements, serving two audiences —
the **director** (you, monitoring ingestion) and a **future client** (CFO / finance
manager / CEO, accessing and sifting content).
**Read against:** `podcast-ingestion-spec.md`, `DESIGN_BRIEF.md`, the live components in
`apps/web/app/(app)/news/podcasts/`, and `packages/shared/src/podcasts.ts`.

---

## TL;DR

The pages are genuinely well built for **one** of their two jobs. As a **director's
ingestion console** they're clear, honest, and tastefully restrained — the spend gauge,
feed-health grid and optimistic row actions are the work of someone who has actually run
a pipeline and been surprised by an invoice.

As a **client-facing knowledge product** they are, today, close to 0% built. That isn't a
criticism of the code — the spec explicitly scoped podcasts as *"not a client-facing
feature"*. But your brief now asks the surface to grow a second head, and the gap is
stark and specific:

> **The single most important finding:** transcripts are chunked and embedded into
> `transcript_segments` (pgvector, 1536-dim) for exactly one reason — semantic retrieval.
> `transcript_segments` is read in **exactly one place** in the entire web app: the
> episode detail page, to render one episode's own transcript. **There is no search
> surface.** The whole payoff of the embedding pipeline — "search episode transcripts the
> same way I search articles", a literal user story in the spec — has no UI. A CFO cannot
> ask the library a single question. That is the headline opportunity.

The second theme: the current page shows **status** ("is a transcript available?") but not
**value** ("what's in it, why does it matter to a treasury audience, and is it actually
searchable yet?"). Those are the two axes a client cares about, and neither is surfaced.

The rest of this doc is the detail, prioritised, with effort tags (S / M / L) and a
recommended build sequence at the end.

