## The core tension: one page, two audiences

The dashboard is titled **"Podcast ingestion"** and is, correctly, an *operations console*.
A CFO does not care about Deepgram spend, feed `last_scanned_at`, or the 30-day uptime
sparkline — those are your concerns, and surfacing them to a client would actively erode
the "serious, credible, not-a-crypto-hype-product" positioning in the design brief.

So the right model is **not** "make the ingestion dashboard prettier for clients." It's
**two experiences over one data spine**:

| | **Director console** (exists) | **Client library** (to build) |
|---|---|---|
| Question it answers | "Is ingestion healthy, what's it costing, what needs me?" | "What's been said about *X*, and what should I take from it?" |
| Primary object | the *feed* and the *pipeline* | the *idea* and the *episode* |
| Surfaces | KPIs, spend gauge, feed health, triage | search, briefs, takeaways, collections |
| Tone | operational, honest about cost | editorial, curated, compliance-safe |
| Who authors the words | nobody (raw show-notes) | an agent, Lex-gated |

Keep `/news/podcasts` as the console. The client experience wants its own route (see P0-1).
The episode page is the **shared spine** — both audiences land on it — so it has to carry
both a provenance sidebar (you) and a synthesised brief (them).

Everything below is sorted into: **A. Director console**, **B. Client library** (the big
build), **C. Episode page**, **D. Cross-cutting** (agents, data model, compliance).

