## A. Director / ops console — findings

The console is 80% there. These are mostly high-value, low-effort fills.

### A1. Show dollars, not just source counts — `S` 🎯

The spend gauge counts *episodes by transcript source*. But Deepgram is billed **per minute
of audio**, and you already store `duration_seconds` per episode and `deepgram_request_id`
on the ones you paid for. Counting episodes hides the truth that one 3-hour Deepgram
episode costs more than ten 12-minute feed-tag ones.

**Do:** add an estimated-spend readout — `Σ(duration_seconds where transcript_source =
'deepgram') × your per-minute rate`, shown as an AUD figure (JetBrains Mono, naturally),
with a "this billing period" and "all time" split. Keep the existing gauge; add the number
beneath it. This is the most on-brand possible dashboard element for *this* company and
it's an afternoon's work.

### A2. A real triage lane, not just a KPI number — `S`

`v_episodes_awaiting_action` exists in the spec precisely for this, but the dashboard
doesn't use it. "Needs attention" is a number in a KPI card; the failed/skipped episodes
themselves are buried behind a table filter. Simon surfaces them over Signal, but the
dashboard — the thing you open when Simon pings you — has no worklist to *act* on.

**Do:** a compact "Needs a decision" section (only rendered when non-empty) listing
`failed` + `skipped` episodes with the failure reason (`transcript_error`) inline and the
one relevant action per row. This is the "close the loop from the Signal message" surface.
`skipped` and `failed` want different default actions (skipped → "turn Deepgram on for this
feed / transcribe once"; failed → "retry / view error").

### A3. Make the one lever that controls spend actionable where you see it — `M`

Feed health surfaces the per-feed Deepgram toggle **read-only**. The dashboard shows you
the consequence of the toggle (coverage %, skipped counts) but makes you leave for
`/news/sources` to pull the lever. That's the wrong place to make the cost decision — you
decide it while looking at the evidence.

**Do:** make the Deepgram pill a real toggle (writes `transcribe_with_deepgram` on
`news_sources`, optimistic, with a confirm because it's a money switch). Bonus: a per-feed
"backfill catalogue" affordance that respects `max_backfill_episodes` / `max_episode_age_days`
so turning a feed on doesn't transcribe a decade overnight — the exact failure the spec
warns about.

### A4. "Available" ≠ "searchable" — surface the embed state — `S` 🎯

`embedded_at` is fetched into `DashboardEpisode` and then... never shown. But an episode
can be `available` (transcript stored) yet not embedded (not in the research index, so Rex
can't retrieve it, so it doesn't exist to a client search). Right now the gap between
"transcribed" and "usable knowledge" is invisible.

**Do:** add "In research index" as a first-class state — a fifth KPI (`count where
embedded_at is not null`) and a subtle indicator on rows/detail. This matters *doubly* once
B (client search) ships, because an un-embedded episode is a silent hole in the library.

### A5. Bulk actions — `M`

Every action is per-row. For a 600-episode back-catalogue (the spec's own example), you
can't select ten `skipped` episodes and transcribe them together, or re-embed a batch after
a chunking change. `DataTable` would need row selection.

**Do (later):** multi-select + a bulk-action bar (fetch / deepgram / retry / re-embed). Not
urgent while volumes are small; will bite the moment you onboard a real catalogue.

### A6. Latency / freshness, not just throughput — `S`

The 30-day area chart answers "did the cron run?" It doesn't answer "how long from ingest
to available?" — the metric that predicts whether a client sees an episode the morning it
drops or three days later. `created_at → transcript_fetched_at → embedded_at` gives you the
pipeline latency for free.

**Do (later):** a small "median time to searchable" stat. Nice-to-have; genuinely useful
once Deepgram (minutes-to-hours) is doing more of the work.

