## B. Client library & briefing — the big build

This is the half that doesn't exist. It's also where the differentiated product lives, so
it gets the most space. Two pillars: **make episodes worth reading** (intelligence) and
**make the library answerable** (search).

### B1. Episode intelligence — summary, takeaways, chapters, entities — `L` 🎯🎯

**The problem:** a CFO will not read a 90-minute raw transcript. The episode page currently
offers exactly that (plus raw HTML show-notes as the "description"). There is no synthesis
layer. The transcript is *evidence*; nobody has done the *reading*.

**The build — an intelligence pass, produced by an agent, stored on the episode:**

- `episode_summary` (TEXT) — 3–5 sentences, BTS house voice, compliance-safe.
- `key_takeaways` (JSONB) — 4–7 bullets, **each anchored to a `start_seconds`** so every
  claim deep-links into the audio/video. This is the treasury-relevant distillation.
- `chapters` (JSONB) — `[{ title, start_seconds }]`. Transforms the transcript from a wall
  into a navigable document, and gives the media player a chapter rail.
- `mentioned_entities` (JSONB) — companies, people, tickers, regulators, dollar figures,
  dates. Deterministic extraction, not vibes (see D1).
- `relevance` — episodes should carry the same **relevance score + category** that
  `news_items` already do (regulatory / corporate / macro / international). Rex already
  scores news; extend the same lens to episodes so a client can sort "most relevant to
  treasury first," not "most recently published."

**How it's built (this is an agents problem, not a UI problem):**

Follow the house **"deterministic before LLM"** rule and the **two-stage extract-then-
narrate** pattern already in play for the daily social pipeline:

1. **Deterministic extract** (a Mastra *tool*, pure, testable): pull entities, numbers,
   tickers, dates, and candidate chapter boundaries from `transcript_segments` — you have
   timestamps, use them. No model needed to find "$21M" or "MicroStrategy."
2. **Narrate** (the agent layer): Roger (or Charlie in a research register) turns the
   structured extract into summary + takeaways in BTS voice, each takeaway carrying the
   `start_seconds` from stage 1 so citations are real, not hallucinated.
3. **Lex gate** (non-negotiable — see D3): a third-party podcast host saying "buy Bitcoin"
   must surface in a BTS client product as *descriptive* ("the host argued X"), never as
   BTS advice. Route the narration through Lex classification before it's ever client-
   visible. This is a natural **Mastra suspend/resume approval gate**, logged to
   `agent_activity` with `proposed → approved`, exactly like the campaigns feature.
4. **Publish-wall:** per your own principle, the client-visible summary only "goes live"
   on approval. Draft summaries stay director-only. The episode page renders the approved
   brief to clients and the raw provenance to you.

This is a big item but it's the one that turns a monitoring page into a knowledge product.
It's also phaseable: `episode_summary` alone (Phase 1) already changes the experience;
takeaways-with-timestamps (Phase 2) and chapters (Phase 3) layer on.

### B2. "Ask the library" — semantic search across transcripts — `M` → `L` 🎯🎯

The embeddings exist and nothing queries them from the web. This is the feature that makes
the back-catalogue an *asset* instead of an archive.

**Minimum (M):** a search route (`/news/podcasts/search` or a client-facing `/library`)
with a query box that runs a `match_transcript_segments` RPC (pgvector cosine similarity)
and returns ranked segments, each showing episode title, the matched passage, a mono
timestamp, and a deep-link into the media at that moment (`{youtube_url}&t={start}s` or an
audio seek — the plumbing for this *already exists* on the episode page). This is Rex's
retrieval, given a UI.

**Elevated (L) — "answer, with receipts":** wrap retrieval in a RAG answer. A CFO types
*"how are companies accounting for bitcoin on the balance sheet?"* and gets a synthesised
2–3 sentence answer **with inline citations** — "Ep. 142 at 23:14", "Ep. 88 at 41:02" —
each a play link. Answer-with-citations is the shape that reads as *trustworthy advisory*
rather than *crypto search engine*, which is precisely the design-brief personality. Lex
sits in front of the answer for the same reason as B1.

> Design note: this is where the "curator note" pays a dividend you can't get elsewhere.
> Because briefs ride a *why*-note into retrieval, the answer can prefer segments a human
> thought were worth saving — contextually intelligent recall, not generic vector match.
> It's the differentiator you already designed for; nothing currently exercises it.

### B3. A browse experience that isn't "Recent (max 4)" — `M`

Today the only "library" gesture is a 4-card recent grid, capped and buried below the
charts, filtered to episodes with playable media. A client arriving to *browse* has nowhere
to go.

**Do:** a proper library view — card grid of episodes (artwork, title, source, duration,
relevance, topic tags), with the *client-relevant* filters (topic, category, source,
"has takeaways") rather than the *ops* filters (transcript status, Deepgram source). Sort
by relevance by default. This is the same data, re-lensed for the reader; it should feel
like a curated shelf, not a job queue.

### B4. Collections / "briefing packs" — `M`

A CFO's real job-to-be-done is often thematic: "get me up to speed on custody" or "what's
the state of the accounting debate." Loose episodes don't serve that; curated sets do.

**Do:** lightweight collections — a named set of episodes (or even individual takeaways/
segments) with a short intro. Manually curated to start (you/Carri assemble them); later,
Charlie can *propose* a collection from a theme and you approve it. A collection is also the
natural unit to eventually hand a client, or to seed a piece of content from — which quietly
connects this to the content pipeline.

### B5. Shareable, exportable artifacts — `S` → `M`

Nothing here leaves the app. A client-facing product needs to produce something a CFO can
forward: "email me this episode's brief," a one-page PDF of a collection, a copy-quote-with-
citation button (`"…quote…" — Guest, Ep. 142 @ 23:14`) on any transcript segment. The
copy-with-citation button is `S` and disproportionately useful; the PDF/email is `M` and
can lean on the existing doc-generation direction elsewhere in the platform.

